These are the basic tools you will need for early crafting and managing Gregtech machines, cables, pipes, etc..

The wrench is used to rotate machines with shift+right click. You can also change connections between cables and pipes.

The wire cutters are used to harvest wires.

The screwdriver is used to allow a machine to input from their output side.

The crowbar is used to remove covers that are placed on machines.

The forestry worktable will allow you to save up to nine recipes in it.

Craft an item and right click it on the right side to "lock" the recipe, it will not be overwritten any time you craft an item and there are already nine recipes saved.
Use the Ender IO conduits to move your steam around. If you want a buffer, you can use Extra Utilities drums or Gregtech multiblock tanks.

The first electrical tier, Low Voltage.

With the start of electrical tiers, here is an explanation on Gregtech power:

Voltage - The max EU/t that a machine can operate at and max amount of EU it can accept. If a machine takes in more voltage than it can handle, it will explode. Do not connect a higher voltage source to a lower voltage without a transformer. It is fine to connect a lower voltage source to a higher voltage.

Amperage - The amount of packets of voltage. For each amp of a certain voltage, it can run a machine of said voltage at max power. So 1A = 1V and 2A = 2V, but at 2V it is still at said voltage tier and will not blow up machines. Certain machines may require more amps to be able to run. Machines will not explode for recieving too many amps. Cables and wires that cannot hold enough amps flowing through it will be destroyed.

Loss - Cables and wires that are not superconductors will have loss per amp per block. Cables will always have less loss than wires except for superconductors, where the wire version will give zero loss anyways. Example: A tin cable has 1 loss, if using a 2x tin wire, it will have 2V lost per block traveled since 2x tin wire holds 2A. Last thing to mention is that powered wires will hurt the player but cables will not, this does not apply to superconductors as you will not get damaged by the wire version.
